    ) VALUES (1350089, 'Lonafarnib', 'Loperamide', 'Major', 'Coadministration with lonafarnib may significantly increase the plasma concentrations of loperamide. The mechanism involves inhibition of CYP450 2C8 and 3A4, the isoenzymes primarily responsible for the metabolic clearance of loperamide. Lonafarnib is a potent CYP450 3A time-dependent and mechanism-based inhibitor and CYP450 2C8 inhibitor in vitro. Additional mechanism of interaction may involve the P-glycoprotein (P-gp) efflux transporter, as lonafarnib is a weak inhibitor of P-gp and loperamide is a substrate. High levels of loperamide, including through abuse or misuse, has been associated with serious and potentially fatal cardiac adverse events such as syncope, cardiac arrest, and arrhythmia related to prolongation of the QT interval.', NULL, 'The initial dosage of loperamide should not exceed 1 mg once daily when coadministered with lonafarnib.', NULL, 'The initial dosage of loperamide should not exceed 1 mg once daily when coadministered with lonafarnib. Subsequently, loperamide dosage may be gradually increased with caution in accordance with its approved product labeling. Patients should seek prompt medical attention if they experience symptoms that could indicate the occurrence of torsade de pointes such as dizziness, lightheadedness, fainting, palpitation, irregular heart rhythm, shortness of breath, or syncope. If loperamide-induced cardiotoxicity is suspected, promptly discontinue loperamide and initiate therapy to manage and prevent cardiac arrhythmias and adverse outcomes. Electrical pacing or cardioversion may be necessary if torsade de pointes persists despite pharmacotherapy. In many of the reported cases of loperamide-induced cardiotoxicity, standard antiarrhythmic drugs were ineffective, and electrical pacing or cardioversion was necessary. The use of loperamide is contraindicated in patients less than 2 years of age.', 'Metabolism', NULL, NULL, 'Major', NULL, 'DDInter', 'pharmacodynamic', 1767317475);
